[Amit Varma]: the Indian laws. And these are laws that I mean, this is the Indian Penal Code, which

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:35.240
[Amit Varma]: we inherited from the British. So very briefly, there's 497 adultery. Now this is I'm not

00:04:35.240 --> 00:04:39.040
[Amit Varma]: going to read this out because it has victorial language, which is an aesthetic affront to

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:45.700
[Amit Varma]: my editorial sensibilities. But the upshot of this is that when adultery is committed,

00:04:45.700 --> 00:04:49.640
[Amit Varma]: the male adulterer who has slept with the wife of someone else is considered at fault

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:55.280
[Amit Varma]: because he slept with that woman without the consent of her husband, as if she is a husband's

00:04:55.280 --> 00:05:00.560
[Amit Varma]: property. And there's this another law 498, which is enticing or taking away or detaining

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:05.160
[Amit Varma]: with criminal intent, a married woman, which really amounts to saying the same thing. I

00:05:05.160 --> 00:05:10.160
[Amit Varma]: encourage you to look these up. But basically, she has no agency whatsoever. Now, this might

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:14.080
[Amit Varma]: seem like an old story. Okay, these are really old laws. We've got them from two centuries

00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:19.600
[Amit Varma]: ago from the British. But the misogyny that is reflected in these ancient laws carries

00:05:19.600 --> 00:05:25.800
[Amit Varma]: down to the present day in the mindset of our lawmakers and our judiciary. And that's

00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:27.040
[Amit Varma]: what we're talking about today.

