00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:46.040
[Guest 1]: triple talaq judgment recently, and how it's supposed to be a champion of women and particularly

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:51.680
[Guest 1]: Muslim women. So does it live up to everything it's supposed to be a champion of?

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:58.320
[Guest 2]: Not really, because the grounds which they used to dismiss triple talaq were not really

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:06.040
[Guest 2]: about the decisional autonomy of the women involved, but just a question of whether it

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:13.680
[Guest 2]: was a quote, unquote, essential religious practice in Muslim personal law. So they said

00:07:13.680 --> 00:07:20.960
[Guest 2]: that it wasn't. And therefore, it was could be subject to constitutional scrutiny. When

00:07:20.960 --> 00:07:27.680
[Guest 2]: I think the reasoning that they should have gone with was that regardless of whether it's

00:07:27.680 --> 00:07:35.040
[Guest 2]: an essential part of a religion or not, any religious practice must subscribe and fall

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:41.440
[Guest 2]: under constitutional principles like equality, and the right to life, to which triple talaq

00:07:41.440 --> 00:07:45.560
[Guest 2]: clearly does not and that should have been the argument that they made, but they didn't.

00:07:45.560 --> 00:07:48.600
